WEBVTT

00:01.543 --> 00:05.923
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:05.923 --> 00:08.926
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:08.926 --> 00:15.682
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:15.682 --> 00:17.226
<i>- My name's Jody Lyddane</i>

00:17.226 --> 00:18.769
from Versailles,
Kentucky.

00:18.769 --> 00:20.729
<i>I've been in the military,</i>

00:20.729 --> 00:22.272
<i>the Kentucky Army</i>
<i>National Guard, for 18 years.</i>

00:22.272 --> 00:24.233
<i>I'm full-time.</i>

00:24.233 --> 00:27.152
So my strategy is to intimidate
all the other players.

00:27.152 --> 00:29.696
I'm kidding. I'm just--
[chuckles]

00:29.696 --> 00:30.948
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:30.948 --> 00:32.991
<i>- My name is Aaron McLean,</i>

00:32.991 --> 00:35.702
and I've been bladesmithing
since I was about 12 years old.

00:35.702 --> 00:39.331
<i>I describe myself</i>
<i>as dedicated.</i>

00:39.331 --> 00:42.042
My arms are made of steel
and my heart is made of coal.

00:43.252 --> 00:45.754
<i>And I will be driven until</i>
<i>the end to prove that I am</i>

00:45.754 --> 00:47.214
<i>the best bladesmith</i>
<i>out there.</i>

00:47.214 --> 00:49.633
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:49.633 --> 00:51.260
<i>- My name is Jason Brown,</i>

00:51.260 --> 00:53.262
<i>and I live in Brevard,</i>
<i>North Carolina.</i>

00:53.262 --> 00:56.640
My daughters and my wife say,
"Man, you need to smile more."

00:56.640 --> 00:58.475
<i>I don't know why</i>
<i>I don't smile.</i>

00:58.475 --> 01:00.352
<i>My mom and dad spent</i>
<i>a fortune on my braces,</i>

01:00.352 --> 01:02.729
but I will smile if I win
"Forged in Fire."

01:02.729 --> 01:05.065
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:05.065 --> 01:07.192
<i>My name is Shawn Shropshire.</i>
<i>I'm from Piedmont, Oklahoma.</i>

01:07.192 --> 01:09.319
I'm pretty confident
that I can win this.

01:09.319 --> 01:11.780
I got a 1 in 4 shot before
we swing a hammer.

01:12.614 --> 01:14.741
<i>If I were to win the money,</i>

01:14.741 --> 01:16.994
<i>my son has already said</i>
<i>we're going on vacation.</i>

01:16.994 --> 01:18.912
I would prefer to use it
for some shop tools,

01:18.912 --> 01:21.248
so maybe we can strike
a balance between the two.

01:21.248 --> 01:22.874
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:22.874 --> 01:26.044
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:26.044 --> 01:28.130
You're all here to engage
in three timed rounds

01:28.130 --> 01:29.756
of edged weapon making
competition

01:29.756 --> 01:32.718
specifically designed
to push every aspect

01:32.718 --> 01:35.470
of your weaponsmithing
capabilities to the limit,

01:35.470 --> 01:37.514
all in front of a panel
of expert judges

01:37.514 --> 01:39.141
who decides which
of you will be our next

01:39.141 --> 01:40.517
"Forged in Fire" champion,

01:40.517 --> 01:45.022
leaving here with a check
for $10,000.

01:45.022 --> 01:46.773
Let's meet your judges now.

01:46.773 --> 01:49.526
Two-time "Forged in Fire"
champion Ben Abbott,

01:49.526 --> 01:52.654
historic weapons re-creation
specialist David Baker,

01:52.654 --> 01:56.325
and last, edged weapons
specialist Doug Marcaida.

01:56.325 --> 01:59.745
Now, if you've paid attention
to previous competitions,

01:59.745 --> 02:02.456
you know that we've had
bladesmiths make

02:02.456 --> 02:05.500
<i>Jay Neilson's favorite blade,</i>
<i>a fluted dagger,</i>

02:05.500 --> 02:09.046
<i>David Baker's favorite blade,</i>
<i>the Scottish dirk,</i>

02:09.046 --> 02:10.380
<i>and, of course,</i>
<i>Doug Marcaida's</i>

02:10.380 --> 02:11.423
<i>favorite weapon,</i>

02:11.423 --> 02:13.133
<i>the karambit.</i>

02:13.133 --> 02:15.302
Well, today, gentlemen,
you will be making

02:15.302 --> 02:18.096
Ben Abbott's favorite blade.

02:18.096 --> 02:19.222
And that blade is...

02:19.222 --> 02:23.310
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:23.310 --> 02:25.270
the Celtic ring knife.

02:25.270 --> 02:27.022
<i>- I am a little bit nervous</i>
<i>that it's going to be</i>

02:27.022 --> 02:28.982
Ben Abbott's signature blade.

02:28.982 --> 02:31.693
I do feel like he would
be pretty particular.

02:31.693 --> 02:33.487
- Now, I'm sure
you're wondering,

02:33.487 --> 02:35.572
"What the hell am I going
to make this blade out of?"

02:35.572 --> 02:37.324
You'll be using this.

02:37.324 --> 02:40.035
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:40.035 --> 02:42.954
That is a wrought iron chain
and some high carbon steel.

02:42.954 --> 02:44.289
- Hmm.

02:44.289 --> 02:46.375
- You'll use the San Mai
technique

02:46.375 --> 02:48.460
to forge your
Celtic ring knives.

02:48.460 --> 02:50.712
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:50.712 --> 02:52.714
<i>- Working with wrought iron--</i>
<i>if it's too cold, it cracks.</i>

02:52.714 --> 02:54.299
<i>If it's too hot, it cracks.</i>

02:54.299 --> 02:56.426
Making it thin enough
that I could use it

02:56.426 --> 02:58.762
in the San Mai construction
worries me.

02:58.762 --> 02:59.930
<i>- The length of your blade</i>
<i>must be</i>

02:59.930 --> 03:02.099
<i>between 12 and 14</i>
<i>inches.</i>

03:02.099 --> 03:03.558
<i>The width of the blade</i>
<i>at the base</i>

03:03.558 --> 03:05.268
<i>must be</i>
<i>at least 2 inches wide.</i>

03:05.268 --> 03:08.105
<i>It must have a full tang</i>
<i>in a drifted</i>

03:08.105 --> 03:09.690
<i>or forge-welded ring.</i>

03:09.690 --> 03:12.109
However, if you look
around this forge,

03:12.109 --> 03:13.985
you'll see all the tools
and equipment you need

03:13.985 --> 03:15.112
to accomplish this task,

03:15.112 --> 03:16.196
with one exception.

03:16.196 --> 03:18.657
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:18.657 --> 03:21.451
You cannot use a drill press.

03:21.451 --> 03:24.287
And that means that any holes
that you put in your blade,

03:24.287 --> 03:26.248
including that ring,

03:26.248 --> 03:28.708
will have to be drifted in
during the forging process.

03:28.708 --> 03:30.585
- I have done very little
with drifts.

03:30.585 --> 03:32.879
<i>Not having</i>
<i>the drill press--</i>

03:32.879 --> 03:34.965
it's going to be challenging.

03:34.965 --> 03:36.591
- Gentlemen,
in the second round,

03:36.591 --> 03:38.176
you'll attach handles
to these blades

03:38.176 --> 03:40.137
turning them into
fully functional weapons

03:40.137 --> 03:42.180
that will be tested for
strength and durability

03:42.180 --> 03:44.724
in an antler chop
meant for edge retention

03:44.724 --> 03:46.059
and a hide slice.

03:46.059 --> 03:47.602
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:47.602 --> 03:50.063
Ben, any advice
for our competitors?

03:50.063 --> 03:52.566
- Don't let the simple shape
of this knife fool you.

03:52.566 --> 03:54.234
There's a lot that you're
going to have to do right

03:54.234 --> 03:56.278
in order to get
a well-proportioned blade.

03:56.278 --> 03:59.281
Also that ring is part
of the grip

03:59.281 --> 04:02.159
and has to be just the right
distance away from the blade

04:02.159 --> 04:04.703
to make a nice comfortable
and secure handle.

04:04.703 --> 04:06.830
Good luck, guys.

04:06.830 --> 04:09.833
- Bladesmiths,
your three hours starts...

04:09.833 --> 04:10.917
now.

04:10.917 --> 04:12.836
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:12.836 --> 04:14.754
So these guys each have
these two links

04:14.754 --> 04:16.631
of wrought iron chain.

04:16.631 --> 04:18.467
They're back there--it looks
like they're cutting them up

04:18.467 --> 04:20.385
together and dipping them up.

04:20.385 --> 04:22.345
Now our high carbon steel,
what type of steel is that?

04:22.345 --> 04:23.972
- It's 1095.

04:23.972 --> 04:25.098
- There's a couple
of different ways

04:25.098 --> 04:26.349
of creating San Mai.

04:26.349 --> 04:28.351
One is the taco method.

04:28.351 --> 04:30.896
<i>The problem is it's hard</i>
<i>to seat that in there</i>

04:30.896 --> 04:33.940
and get a good contact
between that and the core.

04:33.940 --> 04:36.276
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:36.276 --> 04:39.780
<i>The way I'm going to do it is</i>
<i>to use three separate layers</i>

04:39.780 --> 04:41.823
<i>so that I can clamp them</i>
<i>tightly together.</i>

04:41.823 --> 04:44.409
<i>The wrought iron is the softer</i>
<i>of the steels.</i>

04:44.409 --> 04:46.495
It'll be
on the outside layer.

04:46.495 --> 04:49.831
<i>The 1095 core will give you</i>
<i>the hard cutting edge.</i>

04:49.831 --> 04:51.917
- This is a very
difficult challenge.

04:51.917 --> 04:54.544
Some of our smiths here
have not done San Mai before,

04:54.544 --> 04:56.004
and figure out the process.

04:56.004 --> 04:58.632
- It's that setup
that's so important.

04:58.632 --> 05:01.635
Flatten out some material,
clean that material up,

05:01.635 --> 05:03.428
get it ready for a weld.

05:03.428 --> 05:04.638
Make sure you're getting
the welds the way you want 'em

05:04.638 --> 05:06.389
and where you want 'em.

05:06.389 --> 05:07.641
<i>- I feel like I need to get</i>
<i>my blade shaped</i>

05:07.641 --> 05:09.100
before I start
the forge weld.

05:09.100 --> 05:10.393
<i>So I'm gonna get it</i>
<i>to where--</i>

05:10.393 --> 05:11.895
<i>about the length</i>
<i>that I want.</i>

05:11.895 --> 05:13.772
By then, I should have
my wrought iron

05:13.772 --> 05:16.942
heated up enough to form it
into a V shape.

05:16.942 --> 05:19.486
<i>- I think it's a lot harder</i>
<i>to fold a piece of steel</i>

05:19.486 --> 05:21.738
<i>like that than people</i>
<i>think that it is.</i>

05:21.738 --> 05:23.740
<i>- Yeah, biggest challenge is</i>
<i>that wrought iron</i>

05:23.740 --> 05:26.868
and then going back and forth
from one billet to the next.

05:26.868 --> 05:29.454
<i>And don't forget, you know,</i>
<i>that I got something cooking.</i>

05:30.330 --> 05:33.708
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:33.708 --> 05:35.794
- I've worked a little bit
with the San Mai technique,

05:35.794 --> 05:37.838
not a whole lot,
but I get the gist of it.

05:37.838 --> 05:40.048
[gasping] It's hot!

05:40.048 --> 05:43.969
<i>I believe the San Mai</i>
<i>technique is simple enough</i>

05:43.969 --> 05:47.055
that I even, with as limited
experience as I have,

05:47.055 --> 05:48.765
should be able to complete it
no problem.

05:49.808 --> 05:52.936
- Aaron is folding
his wrought iron.

05:52.936 --> 05:56.982
- It would've been nice to see
him draw that out to 3 inches.

05:56.982 --> 05:58.775
So he's got enough material
to wrap around

05:58.775 --> 06:00.151
that high carbon steel.

06:00.151 --> 06:02.279
<i>- So I've got my mild steel</i>

06:02.279 --> 06:04.155
all into the right shape,

06:04.155 --> 06:07.200
and I got my high carbon steel
to the correct length.

06:07.200 --> 06:08.952
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:08.952 --> 06:10.078
Aw, [bleep].

06:10.078 --> 06:11.121
It doesn't fit.

06:11.121 --> 06:12.873
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:12.873 --> 06:15.959
- I've never made a San Mai
or the taco form,

06:15.959 --> 06:18.128
I'm going to do it right now
and see what happens.

06:18.128 --> 06:19.629
<i>The first thing I'm doing is,</i>

06:19.629 --> 06:21.381
I'm just getting
my wrought iron flattened out

06:21.381 --> 06:24.426
and then I'll do the 1095
after I get that finished.

06:24.426 --> 06:26.803
- Jason's not made
a whole lot of progress.

06:26.803 --> 06:30.098
- I'm just hoping he's
consolidating his--his ideas

06:30.098 --> 06:32.309
and he's going
to just leap ahead.

06:32.309 --> 06:33.768
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:33.768 --> 06:36.688
- My forging technique is
pretty slow.

06:37.731 --> 06:39.983
I don't want to make mistakes.
I mean, mistakes is time

06:39.983 --> 06:41.568
<i>and I'm way behind right now.</i>

06:41.568 --> 06:44.654
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:44.654 --> 06:46.239
- Sean's forge weld is set.

06:46.239 --> 06:48.033
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:48.033 --> 06:49.534
<i>- I started shaping</i>
<i>the tip end first,</i>

06:49.534 --> 06:51.161
<i>working myself towards</i>
<i>the handle.</i>

06:51.161 --> 06:54.914
Uh, constantly trying to check
the length of it.

06:54.914 --> 06:57.751
Right now, I'm trying to get
my handle position set.

06:57.751 --> 06:59.628
Uh, so I can figure out
where to put the ring.

06:59.628 --> 07:01.588
- The ring works like a pummel.

07:01.588 --> 07:04.633
It's right there at the pinkie,
but having too much handle--

07:04.633 --> 07:06.885
it tapers down until
it's pencil thin

07:06.885 --> 07:08.928
where that ring is.

07:08.928 --> 07:10.764
Now you're--the meat of your
hand just can't hold onto it.

07:10.764 --> 07:13.016
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:13.016 --> 07:15.101
- Bladesmiths!

07:15.101 --> 07:17.604
One hour has elapsed!

07:17.604 --> 07:19.439
<i>- Today it's my birthday,</i>

07:19.439 --> 07:21.191
and my daughter was trying
to talk me into wearing

07:21.191 --> 07:23.026
a pink birthday sash
out there.

07:23.026 --> 07:24.903
I was like, "I--I don't think
I'm going to do that."

07:24.903 --> 07:27.072
- It's a hell of a way
to spend your birthday.

07:27.072 --> 07:29.032
- Yes, sir.
- Did your wish come true?

07:29.032 --> 07:31.409
- I'll take this.
[laughter]

07:31.409 --> 07:33.453
- So I get my billet
where I want it.

07:33.453 --> 07:35.705
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:35.705 --> 07:40.168
<i>But every time I try to put</i>
<i>the 1095 core into the taco,</i>

07:40.168 --> 07:41.836
<i>it would either pop out</i>
<i>the other end,</i>

07:41.836 --> 07:43.421
<i>it wasn't level.</i>

07:43.421 --> 07:45.048
I tried it upside down,
that didn't work.

07:45.048 --> 07:46.591
<i>I tried it on the floor,</i>
<i>that didn't work.</i>

07:46.591 --> 07:48.093
- He's got a cold piece
of wrought iron

07:48.093 --> 07:49.761
and a hot piece of steel.

07:49.761 --> 07:51.137
- Yeah, you need to go
the other direction with that.

07:51.137 --> 07:53.098
Hot wrought iron,
cold steel.

07:53.098 --> 07:54.599
- Yeah 'cause that way,
if it was a twist or whatever,

07:54.599 --> 07:56.267
you could use the cold steel
to straighten it up

07:56.267 --> 07:58.061
and make everything right
and tight.

07:58.061 --> 08:00.230
<i>- Um, finally I got it</i>
<i>sandwiched.</i>

08:00.230 --> 08:01.856
I know I didn't get
the whole spine,

08:01.856 --> 08:03.274
<i>but it's San Mai.</i>

08:03.274 --> 08:05.819
- It's like he's made
a 1095 blade

08:05.819 --> 08:08.613
and stapled a little
wrought iron at the top.

08:08.613 --> 08:10.156
- That's going
to be a problem

08:10.156 --> 08:11.408
'cause he's not going
to have much mass.

08:11.408 --> 08:14.160
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:14.160 --> 08:17.122
- In the process of
flattening out my wrought iron,

08:17.122 --> 08:19.040
<i>a crack's starting to form.</i>

08:19.040 --> 08:21.376
- He's cracked it.

08:21.376 --> 08:23.002
- This is the worst thing
that could possibly happen

08:23.002 --> 08:24.838
at this moment.

08:24.838 --> 08:26.005
- I'm really starting
to get worried about Jason.

08:26.005 --> 08:27.549
He's spinning his wheels.

08:27.549 --> 08:29.592
<i>- I'm starting</i>
<i>to draw a blank.</i>

08:29.592 --> 08:31.469
I couldn't really think

08:31.469 --> 08:33.888
<i>and then it just</i>
<i>kind of dawned on me.</i>

08:33.888 --> 08:36.474
Those little pieces of chain
link that we cut off,

08:36.474 --> 08:39.936
I'm gonna weld 'em together
into a sandwiched San Mai.

08:39.936 --> 08:43.273
- Jason struggled for so long
before he just decided--

08:43.273 --> 08:46.192
"I'm just gonna stack it up
and then forge a blade."

08:46.192 --> 08:48.194
- If this doesn't work,
then I'm done.

08:48.194 --> 08:50.447
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:50.447 --> 08:52.949
- Right now, the temperature
that Aaron's working at--

08:52.949 --> 08:54.159
- It's not hot enough.

08:54.159 --> 08:56.119
If you work wrought iron cold,

08:56.119 --> 08:58.830
it's got grains of slag in it,
and it can open up

08:58.830 --> 09:01.875
and start to fracture.
- Wow.

09:01.875 --> 09:04.127
<i>- I start to use</i>
<i>the hydraulic press</i>

09:04.127 --> 09:07.255
<i>and realize there's</i>
<i>a huge crack in the taco.</i>

09:07.255 --> 09:09.799
<i>When I look at this piece</i>
<i>of steel,</i>

09:09.799 --> 09:11.134
<i>it's garbage.</i>

09:11.134 --> 09:12.677
So I run over to
the chop saw,

09:12.677 --> 09:14.846
and I find a piece
of mild steel

09:14.846 --> 09:18.224
<i>that I had chopped out off</i>
<i>my billet previously.</i>

09:18.224 --> 09:21.269
I just throw it in and try
to get it heated up

09:21.269 --> 09:22.937
as fast as I can.

09:22.937 --> 09:24.773
<i>Because now</i>
<i>I am very far behind.</i>

09:24.773 --> 09:27.025
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:27.025 --> 09:28.735
- Man, look at Shawn.

09:28.735 --> 09:32.906
He's drifting the hole
or the ring into his blade.

09:32.906 --> 09:34.908
- The ring is giving me
a little bit of problems

09:34.908 --> 09:37.869
trying to get it the
right size, the right shape,

09:37.869 --> 09:40.580
<i>and maintain the integrity</i>
<i>of the steel around it.</i>

09:40.580 --> 09:43.333
The drifts that I've got
aren't quite big enough,

09:43.333 --> 09:45.126
<i>and so I'm having to use</i>
<i>the horn of the handle</i>

09:45.126 --> 09:46.920
<i>a little bit</i>
<i>and then go back and forth</i>

09:46.920 --> 09:49.047
<i>between the drift</i>
<i>and the horn.</i>

09:49.047 --> 09:51.216
<i>This would be immensely easier</i>
<i>if I could use a drill press</i>

09:51.216 --> 09:52.425
<i>on the ring.</i>

09:52.425 --> 09:54.010
Because with a drill press,

09:54.010 --> 09:56.012
it's a simple operation
of just drilling a hole.

09:56.012 --> 09:58.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:58.640 --> 10:01.392
- I flux pound out
of this stuff.

10:01.392 --> 10:04.020
- Oh, man, there's flux
flying everywhere back there.

10:04.020 --> 10:05.730
- Everything is sticking.

10:05.730 --> 10:07.065
Except for that end of it.

10:07.065 --> 10:09.776
- Oh! No, no, no.

10:09.776 --> 10:12.403
- His MIG welds are just
tiny little tacks on the side,

10:12.403 --> 10:14.656
and in hammering on it
on its edge,

10:14.656 --> 10:16.616
they just opened right up.

10:16.616 --> 10:18.993
- It's like problem
after problem after problem.

10:18.993 --> 10:23.373
- Jason is cutting
the unwelded tip of his blade.

10:23.373 --> 10:25.375
I'm nervous of--of him
having enough steel

10:25.375 --> 10:26.751
after that process
to finish.

10:26.751 --> 10:33.049
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:33.049 --> 10:37.387
- I cannot get this piece
of mild steel to weld

10:37.387 --> 10:40.890
<i>to the high carbon steel</i>
<i>in any way.</i>

10:40.890 --> 10:42.892
- Didn't work the first time.

10:42.892 --> 10:44.936
What is he doing different
the second time

10:44.936 --> 10:46.229
that's going to give him
an advantage?

10:46.229 --> 10:48.022
- Nothing.

10:48.022 --> 10:49.941
- What I'd like to see
is, clean that piece--

10:49.941 --> 10:51.442
You know, get that scale off
before you start

10:51.442 --> 10:53.069
driving something else
on top of it.

10:53.069 --> 10:55.029
<i>- It's starting</i>
<i>to get to me.</i>

10:55.029 --> 10:56.823
- Aaron's being crushed
right now.

10:56.823 --> 10:58.700
- Damn it.

10:58.700 --> 11:00.702
- Aaron's struggling, man.

11:00.702 --> 11:03.705
<i>- I'm looking at the clock,</i>
<i>and I realize</i>

11:03.705 --> 11:06.207
I don't think I'll be able
to complete this challenge.

11:06.207 --> 11:07.041
- Come on, man.

11:10.545 --> 11:12.422
- Aaron's struggling, man.

11:12.422 --> 11:14.507
<i>- I didn't take the time</i>

11:14.507 --> 11:17.051
to clean them out with that
wire brush like I should've,

11:17.051 --> 11:19.637
<i>and I'm regretting it now.</i>

11:19.637 --> 11:22.891
<i>I need to get this piece</i>
<i>of metal to stick,</i>

11:22.891 --> 11:24.684
no matter what it takes.

11:24.684 --> 11:28.146
- It's always a good idea
to MIG weld both ends

11:28.146 --> 11:30.982
at a couple of places
along the edge

11:30.982 --> 11:32.734
so things don't move.

11:32.734 --> 11:36.237
<i>- So I welded</i>
<i>both sides of this knife,</i>

11:36.237 --> 11:38.156
and it's finally sticking.

11:38.156 --> 11:40.200
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:40.200 --> 11:43.203
<i>And I'm trying to get</i>
<i>some sort of basic shape.</i>

11:43.203 --> 11:45.830
So I put everything
I have left in me

11:45.830 --> 11:47.707
<i>into that billet.</i>
[bleep]

11:47.707 --> 11:49.626
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:49.626 --> 11:53.296
- Jody is starting to drift
the hole into his blade.

11:53.296 --> 11:55.840
<i>- I knew the--the hole</i>
<i>was going to be an issue.</i>

11:55.840 --> 11:58.384
I'm really focused
on maintaining this hole

11:58.384 --> 12:01.930
'cause if you expand too much
beyond an 1 1/4 inches,

12:01.930 --> 12:03.056
you're done.

12:03.056 --> 12:05.058
- 30 minutes, bladesmiths!

12:05.058 --> 12:07.310
You got it, fellas!
Stay in the fight!

12:07.310 --> 12:09.312
♪ ♪

12:09.312 --> 12:11.689
- All right.

12:11.689 --> 12:13.775
<i>- When I pull the knife</i>
<i>out of the quench,</i>

12:13.775 --> 12:15.109
I realize I got
a pretty good warp.

12:15.109 --> 12:16.236
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:16.236 --> 12:17.487
- Hey!

12:17.487 --> 12:19.197
Ah, that's a lot of motion.

12:19.197 --> 12:21.449
<i>- There's a small window</i>
<i>there where you do</i>

12:21.449 --> 12:23.201
<i>have some flexibility.</i>

12:23.201 --> 12:26.537
It can be pretty risky,
because if you drop below

12:26.537 --> 12:29.415
a certain temperature,
you snap your blade.

12:29.415 --> 12:31.709
- Oh, man.

12:31.709 --> 12:32.752
- Oh.
- Whoa.

12:32.752 --> 12:35.630
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:35.630 --> 12:38.758
- Jason is really making
a comeback.

12:38.758 --> 12:40.802
- For a guy that--
honestly, I was worried

12:40.802 --> 12:42.095
there was about to throw
in the towel.

12:42.095 --> 12:43.554
- Yeah.
- He really regrouped.

12:43.554 --> 12:45.890
<i>- I almost gave up.</i>

12:45.890 --> 12:49.894
<i>But I produced a blade,</i>
<i>when in my mind I was done.</i>

12:49.894 --> 12:51.145
I may actually have
a chance.

12:51.145 --> 12:53.439
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:53.439 --> 12:55.608
- Right now, I'm so close
to meeting all the parameters.

12:55.608 --> 12:58.736
Um, the only issue
I'm having is my width.

12:58.736 --> 13:00.947
So I'm--I'm about
an 1/8 of an inch off.

13:00.947 --> 13:03.825
Um, I think I can pull enough
steel up from the handle.

13:03.825 --> 13:07.287
- He's chasing this width,
and it's just not there.

13:07.287 --> 13:09.580
So he's really thinned out
his material right there

13:09.580 --> 13:11.624
where the handle
meets the blade.

13:11.624 --> 13:15.295
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:15.295 --> 13:16.963
- I'll take it.

13:16.963 --> 13:20.008
- Five, four, three,

13:20.008 --> 13:22.093
two, one.

13:22.093 --> 13:23.720
All right, bladesmiths,
good job.

13:23.720 --> 13:26.431
This first round
of competition is over.

13:26.431 --> 13:29.058
<i>- I didn't produce</i>
<i>a blade like I wanted to.</i>

13:29.058 --> 13:31.519
<i>It's just a knife shaped</i>
<i>piece of steel.</i>

13:31.519 --> 13:33.354
I'm a little worried.

13:33.354 --> 13:35.106
- All right, bladesmiths,
our first round

13:35.106 --> 13:37.567
of weaponsmithing competition
is over.

13:37.567 --> 13:39.610
In the first round,
we asked you guys to forge

13:39.610 --> 13:41.029
Ben Abbott's favorite knife,

13:41.029 --> 13:42.488
a Celtic ring knife.

13:42.488 --> 13:43.781
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:43.781 --> 13:45.199
Now it's time for
the judges

13:45.199 --> 13:46.367
to take a closer look
at your work.

13:46.367 --> 13:47.952
Shawn, you're up first.

13:47.952 --> 13:50.121
Please present your blade
to the judges.

13:50.121 --> 13:52.081
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:52.081 --> 13:53.875
<i>- All right, Shawn.</i>

13:53.875 --> 13:55.543
<i>Overall, I love the profile</i>
<i>of your blade.</i>

13:55.543 --> 13:58.212
<i>Definitely looks like</i>
<i>it's ready for action.</i>

13:58.212 --> 14:00.339
<i>On the other hand,</i>
<i>the handle,</i>

14:00.339 --> 14:02.633
because of its length,
it's going to slide around.

14:02.633 --> 14:05.970
The purpose of the ring
is to act as an anchor.

14:05.970 --> 14:09.432
So if I slide up here, there's
nothing to anchor that.

14:09.432 --> 14:11.851
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:11.851 --> 14:14.062
- Well, Shawn, I've noticed

14:14.062 --> 14:16.481
<i>it's got</i>
<i>a pretty serious warp</i>

14:16.481 --> 14:18.399
kind of kicking off
that way.

14:18.399 --> 14:20.943
But I think it's not something
that's beyond fixing.

14:20.943 --> 14:22.779
- Thank you.

14:22.779 --> 14:25.823
- Jason, please present
your blade to the judges.

14:25.823 --> 14:27.158
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:27.158 --> 14:29.118
<i>- I like that a lot.</i>

14:29.118 --> 14:32.038
<i>That profile's real nice.</i>
<i>It's almost there.</i>

14:32.038 --> 14:35.249
<i>A lot of refinement to do,</i>
<i>but what I like is that you've</i>

14:35.249 --> 14:38.252
left yourself enough material
to do those refinements.

14:38.252 --> 14:41.047
There's some issues with
some delaminations up here

14:41.047 --> 14:42.924
on your edge.

14:42.924 --> 14:45.134
<i>I'm hoping that those are</i>
<i>just on your edge,</i>

14:45.134 --> 14:46.803
and if you lose a little bit
more of that,

14:46.803 --> 14:48.179
you'll be in good shape.

14:48.179 --> 14:49.639
Good job.
- All right, thank you.

14:49.639 --> 14:51.182
- All right, Jody,
you're up.

14:51.182 --> 14:53.017
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:53.017 --> 14:54.936
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:54.936 --> 14:56.813
<i>- Well, Jody,</i>
<i>the first thing I notice</i>

14:56.813 --> 14:59.273
<i>when I pick up this knife</i>
<i>is, it's really lean.</i>

14:59.273 --> 15:01.150
<i>I saw your tactic</i>
<i>of using a little</i>

15:01.150 --> 15:02.443
<i>of the wrought iron</i>
<i>as you had to,</i>

15:02.443 --> 15:04.862
but I think doing that,

15:04.862 --> 15:07.073
you sacrificed some of the mass
you could've had.

15:07.073 --> 15:09.200
One thing that is
of some concern

15:09.200 --> 15:12.370
is there's a pretty decent
warp, uh, on here.

15:12.370 --> 15:13.871
You know, you can--

15:13.871 --> 15:15.498
you can see that

15:15.498 --> 15:17.041
when you hit it
from either side.

15:17.041 --> 15:20.920
But it's something
that can be taken out.

15:20.920 --> 15:22.755
In general, I mean,
it's solid.

15:22.755 --> 15:25.716
The--the welds look
to be pretty solid.

15:25.716 --> 15:27.844
So nicely done.

15:27.844 --> 15:30.596
- Aaron,

15:30.596 --> 15:32.473
you had some trouble
out there.

15:32.473 --> 15:34.308
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:34.308 --> 15:36.644
<i>Your blade doesn't have</i>
<i>a ring.</i>

15:36.644 --> 15:38.354
<i>There's no defined</i>
<i>blade shape.</i>

15:38.354 --> 15:40.940
<i>Your forge welds</i>
<i>haven't been set.</i>

15:40.940 --> 15:43.317
You worked until
the very last minute,

15:43.317 --> 15:45.611
but I'm not going to ask you
to present your blade

15:45.611 --> 15:46.988
to the judges.

15:46.988 --> 15:48.573
You understand why?
- I do.

15:48.573 --> 15:50.158
- Nobody's here
to tear you down.

15:50.158 --> 15:51.325
Just to show up here
in The Forge

15:51.325 --> 15:52.702
is an accomplishment.

15:52.702 --> 15:54.370
But at this time,
I have to ask you

15:54.370 --> 15:55.538
to please surrender
your steel

15:55.538 --> 15:56.664
and leave The Forge.

15:56.664 --> 15:59.709
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:59.709 --> 16:01.711
<i>- The biggest thing that I</i>
<i>learned from this competition</i>

16:01.711 --> 16:03.629
<i>was that I need</i>
<i>to take my time</i>

16:03.629 --> 16:06.507
and I need not to rush
through all of my tasks

16:06.507 --> 16:08.426
and try to get
to the next one.

16:08.426 --> 16:10.761
<i>From here, I take all of</i>
<i>the lessons I have learned,</i>

16:10.761 --> 16:12.263
<i>and I grow from them.</i>

16:12.263 --> 16:14.348
And hopefully, one day,
I'll be back.

16:14.348 --> 16:19.061
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:19.061 --> 16:20.938
- All right, bladesmiths,
congratulations.

16:20.938 --> 16:23.316
All of your blades
have made parameters,

16:23.316 --> 16:25.860
and you're moving into
this next round of competition

16:25.860 --> 16:27.570
and now that those blades
have been tempered,

16:27.570 --> 16:30.114
it's time to turn them into
fully functional weapons

16:30.114 --> 16:31.866
by attaching handles to them.

16:31.866 --> 16:34.785
You must use natural materials
on your handles.

16:34.785 --> 16:38.497
That's bone, horn, hide,
leather, cord.

16:38.497 --> 16:39.999
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:39.999 --> 16:41.334
You have three hours
in this round

16:41.334 --> 16:43.044
in which to complete
your work.

16:43.044 --> 16:45.338
Good luck, bladesmiths.
Your three hours starts...

16:45.338 --> 16:47.340
now.

16:47.340 --> 16:48.925
- I am way more jazzed than
I thought I was going to be

16:48.925 --> 16:50.801
about watching these
three guys make my knife.

16:50.801 --> 16:52.678
You know,
it's just so much fun.

16:52.678 --> 16:55.681
- Does it make you a little bit
more critical of their work?

16:55.681 --> 16:56.766
- Yeah, a little.

16:56.766 --> 16:58.100
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:58.100 --> 17:00.228
- Does it make it easier?

17:00.228 --> 17:02.271
No pins are required.

17:02.271 --> 17:04.774
So it's basically scales,
glue, and wrap.

17:04.774 --> 17:06.609
- There's some art to doing
the rawhide.

17:06.609 --> 17:08.653
You have to soak it first,
let it expand a little bit.

17:08.653 --> 17:10.529
When it's wet, it stretches.

17:10.529 --> 17:12.448
But it's also relatively weak.

17:12.448 --> 17:15.326
So if you were trying to get
a good, strong wrap on it,

17:15.326 --> 17:17.078
you're gonna snap it.

17:17.078 --> 17:19.914
So this handle fit-up
is kind of the definition

17:19.914 --> 17:21.791
of the difference between
simple and easy.

17:21.791 --> 17:23.542
Like a marathon is simple.

17:23.542 --> 17:25.044
You just keep running
until you're done.

17:25.044 --> 17:26.462
It's not easy.
- Yeah.

17:26.462 --> 17:28.506
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:28.506 --> 17:30.091
<i>- It feels good to be going</i>
<i>into the second round.</i>

17:30.091 --> 17:31.842
Now it's time to fix
the problems I made

17:31.842 --> 17:33.469
in the first round.

17:33.469 --> 17:36.055
There's a pretty significant
warp in my blade.

17:36.055 --> 17:38.516
<i>I wish I had more meat</i>
<i>to grind off of it,</i>

17:38.516 --> 17:40.977
<i>but I'll have to make do</i>
<i>with what I got</i>

17:40.977 --> 17:43.020
and then fix the handle.

17:43.020 --> 17:44.647
<i>What I'm going to do</i>
<i>is go ahead</i>

17:44.647 --> 17:47.942
and just cut a section
out of the center.

17:47.942 --> 17:49.360
<i>Re-weld that together</i>

17:49.360 --> 17:51.779
and place the handle
over the weld.

17:51.779 --> 17:53.823
- Shawn has welded
that ring on there.

17:53.823 --> 17:57.076
That handle looks like it's got
a nice scale to the blade now.

17:57.076 --> 17:59.662
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:59.662 --> 18:03.040
- Right now
my biggest concern is this.

18:03.040 --> 18:05.251
It's a delamination
in my blade.

18:05.251 --> 18:08.087
<i>Delamination means I didn't</i>
<i>get a good forge weld on it</i>

18:08.087 --> 18:11.465
<i>and if I don't get it fixed,</i>
<i>when they do the antler chop,</i>

18:11.465 --> 18:13.217
it can just completely
blow apart.

18:13.217 --> 18:14.885
- It may just be

18:14.885 --> 18:17.430
that those pieces of
wrought iron lift over.

18:17.430 --> 18:19.015
A little bit
of grinding is going

18:19.015 --> 18:20.141
to expose that hard steel
in the middle.

18:20.141 --> 18:21.142
- Yeah.

18:21.142 --> 18:23.227
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:23.227 --> 18:24.854
<i>- So my game plan is</i>

18:24.854 --> 18:26.355
<i>to address all</i>
<i>the judges' issues,</i>

18:26.355 --> 18:28.274
including the little bit
of a warp.

18:28.274 --> 18:30.484
<i>I think I can grind most</i>
<i>of that out.</i>

18:30.484 --> 18:32.778
My biggest concern is
the thinness of my blade.

18:32.778 --> 18:34.655
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:34.655 --> 18:36.407
- It's going to come down
to a lot of edge geometry

18:36.407 --> 18:38.367
on these blades.

18:38.367 --> 18:40.995
For an antler chop, especially,
you know it's so hard--

18:40.995 --> 18:42.830
just the littlest bit
of torqueing when you hit

18:42.830 --> 18:44.665
can just snap.

18:44.665 --> 18:46.125
<i>There's nothing easy</i>
<i>about this challenge.</i>

18:46.125 --> 18:47.835
<i>You know,</i>
<i>you always have pins.</i>

18:47.835 --> 18:50.254
This is a little bit out
of my comfort zone

18:50.254 --> 18:53.299
just doing a leather wrap
and epoxy.

18:53.299 --> 18:54.508
- Bladesmiths,

18:54.508 --> 18:57.386
60 minutes has elapsed!

18:57.386 --> 19:00.640
You have two hours remaining
to finish your blades.

19:00.640 --> 19:04.226
- My handle material is two
pieces of similar looking palm,

19:04.226 --> 19:07.772
some leather wrap,
and, uh, that's about it.

19:07.772 --> 19:10.274
- So you glued
the handle scales on first...

19:10.274 --> 19:11.609
- Yeah.

19:11.609 --> 19:12.943
- Shape it,
and then wrap things up.

19:12.943 --> 19:14.487
- Yeah, that's right.
- Okay.

19:14.487 --> 19:15.571
<i>- My major concern,</i>
<i>at this point,</i>

19:15.571 --> 19:17.323
<i>is the warp on the blade.</i>

19:17.323 --> 19:19.200
<i>I feel like, since I</i>
<i>started grinding on it.</i>

19:19.200 --> 19:21.160
<i>the wrap is--</i>
<i>has gotten worse.</i>

19:21.160 --> 19:23.037
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:23.037 --> 19:24.997
I'm gonna try to get
the handle on, get it set,

19:24.997 --> 19:26.290
then do whatever
I can to correct any issues

19:26.290 --> 19:27.291
with the blade.

19:27.291 --> 19:29.001
<i>For the handle material,</i>

19:29.001 --> 19:31.087
<i>I'm going to go with</i>
<i>a piece of hardwood</i>

19:31.087 --> 19:32.838
<i>and then a rawhide wrap.</i>

19:32.838 --> 19:35.299
Not having to put the pins
in saves me some time

19:35.299 --> 19:37.718
<i>because it's less work</i>
<i>that I have to do.</i>

19:37.718 --> 19:39.720
But I have to do
everything else well

19:39.720 --> 19:41.430
<i>to make sure that</i>
<i>the handle is secure.</i>

19:41.430 --> 19:43.516
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:43.516 --> 19:46.852
<i>The rawhide wrap acts as</i>
<i>a replacement for those pins.</i>

19:46.852 --> 19:49.271
Uh, when the rawhide dries,
it'll bind up.

19:49.271 --> 19:51.273
and should secure the handle.

19:51.273 --> 19:53.693
I've heard rawhide described
as cowboy duct tape.

19:53.693 --> 19:55.695
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:55.695 --> 19:57.530
<i>- As I'm at the grinder,</i>

19:57.530 --> 19:59.782
<i>I'm still chasing</i>
<i>the delamination</i>

19:59.782 --> 20:03.035
<i>and I'm trying</i>
<i>to get rid of the wrought iron</i>

20:03.035 --> 20:04.954
<i>and I'm trying</i>
<i>to expose the 1095</i>

20:04.954 --> 20:06.539
for my cutting edge.

20:06.539 --> 20:09.500
- Jason is walking over
to an etch bucket.

20:09.500 --> 20:10.835
- He's going
to find that edge.

20:10.835 --> 20:12.294
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:12.294 --> 20:14.922
- The 1095 was all black

20:14.922 --> 20:17.591
<i>and the wrought iron</i>
<i>pretty much just stayed gray.</i>

20:17.591 --> 20:18.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:18.968 --> 20:20.302
[bleep]

20:20.302 --> 20:23.013
- And Jason's back
to the grinder.

20:23.013 --> 20:25.975
<i>- The only 1095 I see</i>
<i>is in the very--</i>

20:25.975 --> 20:28.519
probably last 3 inches
of my blade.

20:28.519 --> 20:32.022
- The wrought iron isn't as
hard as the high carbon steel.

20:32.022 --> 20:33.899
If he's got
a soft blade edge,

20:33.899 --> 20:35.985
what do you think is going
to happen on the antler?

20:35.985 --> 20:38.821
- The antler chop is gonna
dull it, fold it.

20:38.821 --> 20:40.948
That's going to affect
the sharpness test.

20:40.948 --> 20:42.616
<i>- As I grind</i>
<i>more and more away,</i>

20:42.616 --> 20:44.201
<i>I'm afraid it's weakening</i>
<i>my blade.</i>

20:44.201 --> 20:45.411
So when it comes
to the strength test,

20:45.411 --> 20:47.037
it could fail it.

20:47.037 --> 20:49.707
And the more I grind,
the worse it gets.

20:49.707 --> 20:51.709
- Jody's got his handle
glued on.

20:51.709 --> 20:55.588
Shawn's got his handle glued on
and wrapped at this point.

20:55.588 --> 20:57.298
These guys are really
about the details.

20:57.298 --> 20:59.216
- Yeah.

20:59.216 --> 21:01.010
- One of my favorite things
about knife making is

21:01.010 --> 21:02.636
doing the handles.

21:02.636 --> 21:04.346
<i>It allows me to use</i>
<i>my imagination.</i>

21:04.346 --> 21:06.140
I've got plenty of time.

21:06.140 --> 21:08.934
<i>So I thought why not put</i>
<i>a little Celtic design</i>

21:08.934 --> 21:10.978
on the blade before I put
the leather on.

21:10.978 --> 21:13.230
<i>If all three blades</i>
<i>perform the same,</i>

21:13.230 --> 21:15.566
it may come down to
whose is designed better.

21:15.566 --> 21:18.694
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:18.694 --> 21:20.696
- 30 minutes, bladesmiths!

21:20.696 --> 21:23.282
- Shawn--Shawn's got an issue.

21:23.282 --> 21:25.743
Shawn has ground a warp
into his blade.

21:25.743 --> 21:27.411
- Oh, really?
- By grinding--

21:27.411 --> 21:30.873
the heat of the grinding
caused it to warp more.

21:30.873 --> 21:32.833
<i>- I'm gonna try to soften</i>
<i>the spine,</i>

21:32.833 --> 21:34.418
<i>see if I can relax</i>
<i>the blade a little bit,</i>

21:34.418 --> 21:35.920
<i>take a little bit</i>
<i>of that warp out.</i>

21:35.920 --> 21:37.755
<i>Everything can go wrong</i>
<i>at this point.</i>

21:37.755 --> 21:40.132
<i>The blade can break.</i>
<i>It can warp worse.</i>

21:40.132 --> 21:41.926
It's all or nothing now.

21:41.926 --> 21:43.552
- Oh, boy.

21:43.552 --> 21:45.721
<i>- There are knots in</i>
<i>my stomach.</i>

21:45.721 --> 21:47.598
- Man.

21:47.598 --> 21:49.558
<i>- If it breaks, I'm out.</i>

21:49.558 --> 21:50.726
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:55.064 --> 21:56.816
<i>- Everything can go wrong</i>
<i>at this point.</i>

21:56.816 --> 21:58.818
<i>The blade can break.</i>
<i>It can warp worse.</i>

21:58.818 --> 22:00.110
- Oh, boy.

22:00.110 --> 22:06.242
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:06.242 --> 22:08.327
- Wow. He got away with it.

22:08.327 --> 22:10.204
<i>- At this point, I've got</i>
<i>the blade as straight</i>

22:10.204 --> 22:12.373
as I can safely.

22:12.373 --> 22:13.958
<i>So I start working on</i>
<i>my cutting edge</i>

22:13.958 --> 22:15.251
and refining
the blade itself.

22:15.251 --> 22:17.837
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:17.837 --> 22:21.131
<i>- I'm at a point where</i>
<i>I need to stop grinding.</i>

22:21.131 --> 22:22.550
I got to focus on
the handle.

22:22.550 --> 22:24.927
- Jason has picked sheep horn,

22:24.927 --> 22:27.429
which is really tough,
really durable,

22:27.429 --> 22:29.265
but it takes a little bit
more grinding

22:29.265 --> 22:30.975
than some of the woods
that we have.

22:30.975 --> 22:32.476
- Right now, I'm feeling
the pressure of the clock.

22:32.476 --> 22:34.186
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:34.186 --> 22:36.814
<i>I'm--I'm trying to get</i>
<i>the scales even.</i>

22:36.814 --> 22:39.149
I'm struggling with that and,
uh, it's setting up now

22:39.149 --> 22:41.360
and I--I pretty much
just got to tighten it down

22:41.360 --> 22:42.486
<i>and leave it.</i>

22:42.486 --> 22:44.113
- Ten minutes!

22:44.113 --> 22:45.781
Ten minutes, gentlemen.

22:45.781 --> 22:48.284
<i>- I am a</i>
<i>extreme perfectionist,</i>

22:48.284 --> 22:50.077
<i>but I'm rushing now.</i>

22:50.077 --> 22:51.662
It's going to be
a little rough.

22:51.662 --> 22:53.330
Right now, I'm just making it
functional.

22:53.330 --> 22:56.834
I have to get my hide wrap
onto this handle.

22:56.834 --> 22:58.335
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:58.335 --> 23:00.379
- Man, we're coming down
to the wire here.

23:00.379 --> 23:02.131
<i>- I'm--I'm not worried</i>
<i>about the correct way.</i>

23:02.131 --> 23:03.799
I'm just trying
to get it on.

23:03.799 --> 23:05.634
- Oh, man. Oh, no.

23:05.634 --> 23:07.136
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:07.136 --> 23:09.972
- Five, four, three,

23:09.972 --> 23:11.974
two, one.

23:11.974 --> 23:13.934
Bladesmiths,

23:13.934 --> 23:16.812
this second round of Celtic
ring knife competition

23:16.812 --> 23:18.230
is over!

23:18.230 --> 23:20.232
- Wow, that was awesome.

23:20.232 --> 23:22.651
<i>- I'm just happy right now</i>
<i>I finished my blade.</i>

23:22.651 --> 23:24.612
I mean,
in my mind I was done

23:24.612 --> 23:26.363
a couple of times.

23:26.363 --> 23:28.365
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the strength test.

23:28.365 --> 23:29.950
The antler chop.

23:29.950 --> 23:31.827
To test the strength
and durability

23:31.827 --> 23:33.495
of your Celtic ring knife
blades

23:33.495 --> 23:35.539
as well as
the overall construction,

23:35.539 --> 23:38.208
I'm going to be bashing them
into these antlers.

23:38.208 --> 23:39.084
Jody, you're up.
You ready?

23:39.084 --> 23:41.253
- I am.

23:41.253 --> 23:44.882
<i>No one's not gonna be worried</i>
<i>about an antler chop,</i>

23:44.882 --> 23:47.885
<i>but I know I'm very sharp.</i>

23:47.885 --> 23:49.845
<i>I think it's strong.</i>

23:49.845 --> 23:51.847
I've got high expectations
for my blade.

23:51.847 --> 23:53.140
I think it's a good blade.

23:53.140 --> 23:55.059
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:55.059 --> 23:58.145
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

23:58.145 --> 24:04.735
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:04.735 --> 24:05.861
[metallic clink]

24:05.861 --> 24:08.155
♪ ♪

24:08.155 --> 24:09.156
- Oh!

24:09.156 --> 24:10.950
[metallic clanking]

24:10.950 --> 24:13.619
- Dang it.

24:13.619 --> 24:14.662
Wow.

24:14.662 --> 24:16.121
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:16.121 --> 24:17.581
- Well, Jody,

24:17.581 --> 24:19.416
it's evident what happened.

24:19.416 --> 24:22.628
If you look very closely
at the end of the weld here,

24:22.628 --> 24:24.254
there's a spot that,
during the tempering,

24:24.254 --> 24:25.923
took some oxidation.

24:25.923 --> 24:28.050
That crack was there
ready to fail at any time.

24:28.050 --> 24:29.718
- Got it.

24:29.718 --> 24:31.679
- But the edge itself
held up well

24:31.679 --> 24:33.931
and, uh, I think
you did a good job.

24:33.931 --> 24:35.766
- Thank you.

24:35.766 --> 24:38.936
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:38.936 --> 24:42.064
- Jody, your blade has suffered
a catastrophic blade failure

24:42.064 --> 24:44.817
after five strikes
on that antler.

24:44.817 --> 24:46.360
Doesn't mean you're out
of this competition.

24:46.360 --> 24:48.320
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:48.320 --> 24:51.532
Jason, Shawn. Your blades must
survive five strikes

24:51.532 --> 24:53.826
in this strength test
in order to move forward.

24:53.826 --> 24:54.910
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:54.910 --> 24:56.286
Good luck.
Ben?

24:56.286 --> 24:57.329
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:57.329 --> 24:58.998
- Now I'm nervous.

24:58.998 --> 25:00.457
- Jason, you're up.

25:00.457 --> 25:02.376
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:02.376 --> 25:04.795
<i>- I'm very nervous about</i>
<i>my blade making it through</i>

25:04.795 --> 25:06.672
<i>the five chops.</i>

25:06.672 --> 25:08.841
<i>The hide wrap--I didn't</i>
<i>get them on correctly.</i>

25:08.841 --> 25:10.884
And my scales could pop off.

25:10.884 --> 25:12.928
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:12.928 --> 25:14.930
[muttering indistinctly]

25:14.930 --> 25:17.891
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

25:17.891 --> 25:24.815
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:26.191 --> 25:29.153
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

25:29.153 --> 25:30.738
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:30.738 --> 25:32.364
- Well, Jason,

25:32.364 --> 25:34.742
it took some pretty serious
chipping here.

25:34.742 --> 25:36.201
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:36.201 --> 25:38.537
The handle dimensions
are comfortable,

25:38.537 --> 25:40.497
but this rawhide bit
into my fingers

25:40.497 --> 25:42.291
because it's just hard
and sharp.

25:42.291 --> 25:44.793
But it's one piece.
Very well done.

25:44.793 --> 25:46.545
- Thank you.

25:46.545 --> 25:48.464
- Shawn, you're up next.
Are you ready for this?

25:48.464 --> 25:50.257
- As ready as I'm going to be.

25:50.257 --> 25:52.301
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:52.301 --> 25:54.428
<i>I wish I had more meat</i>
<i>in the spine of my blade.</i>

25:54.428 --> 25:56.513
<i>I'm second-guessing</i>
<i>every decision I made</i>

25:56.513 --> 25:58.307
<i>all along the way now.</i>

25:58.307 --> 26:00.267
This is the make it or
break it test. Literally.

26:00.267 --> 26:02.019
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:02.019 --> 26:04.938
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

26:04.938 --> 26:09.651
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:09.651 --> 26:12.529
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:15.741 --> 26:20.120
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:20.120 --> 26:21.872
- Good job.
- Thanks.

26:21.872 --> 26:24.833
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:24.833 --> 26:25.959
- Well, Shawn,

26:25.959 --> 26:27.711
this is a really nice knife.

26:27.711 --> 26:30.923
I like the shape of it.
Your edge held up beautifully.

26:30.923 --> 26:32.257
Really well done.

26:32.257 --> 26:34.301
- Thank you very much.

26:34.301 --> 26:36.595
- Jody,
this is a competition

26:36.595 --> 26:38.180
where the best blades
move forward,

26:38.180 --> 26:40.599
and, unfortunately, that
catastrophic blade failure

26:40.599 --> 26:42.768
means you can no longer
continue with testing.

26:42.768 --> 26:44.269
And for that reason,
I have to ask you

26:44.269 --> 26:46.980
to please leave The Forge.

26:46.980 --> 26:48.607
<i>- If my last 18 years</i>
<i>in the military</i>

26:48.607 --> 26:51.193
has taught me anything,
it's adapt and overcome.

26:51.193 --> 26:52.444
<i>I'm probably going</i>
<i>to make this knife</i>

26:52.444 --> 26:54.488
<i>again and again</i>

26:54.488 --> 26:57.116
<i>just so I can prove to myself</i>
<i>that I can still do it.</i>

26:57.116 --> 26:58.909
Even though I'm not moving
on to round three,

26:58.909 --> 27:02.121
<i>I couldn't pick two better</i>
<i>smiths to lose to.</i>

27:02.121 --> 27:04.832
These guys are exceptional.
I wish them the best.

27:04.832 --> 27:09.002
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:09.002 --> 27:10.963
- Jason, Shawn,
congratulations.

27:10.963 --> 27:13.090
You've made it to the final
round of this competition.

27:13.090 --> 27:15.008
When you guys showed up
to The Forge,

27:15.008 --> 27:17.511
we asked you to forge our judge
Ben Abbott's favorite knife,

27:17.511 --> 27:19.263
the Celtic ring knife.

27:19.263 --> 27:20.764
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

27:20.764 --> 27:22.808
to re-create an iconic weapon
from history

27:22.808 --> 27:25.227
from the same kilted region.

27:25.227 --> 27:26.562
That weapon is...

27:26.562 --> 27:29.857
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:29.857 --> 27:31.984
The Irish ring-hilted sword.

27:31.984 --> 27:33.694
- Oof.

27:33.694 --> 27:35.863
<i>- Dating back</i>
<i>to the 12th century,</i>

27:35.863 --> 27:38.156
<i>the Irish ring-hilted sword</i>
<i>was a classic European weapon</i>

27:38.156 --> 27:41.118
<i>with a blade reaching lengths</i>
<i>of up to 40 inches.</i>

27:41.118 --> 27:43.579
<i>The broad double-edged weapon</i>
<i>featured a distinctive</i>

27:43.579 --> 27:45.914
<i>ring pommel that was key</i>
<i>for counterbalancing</i>

27:45.914 --> 27:47.457
<i>its weight,</i>

27:47.457 --> 27:49.293
<i>allowing for swift</i>
<i>and deadly cuts.</i>

27:49.293 --> 27:51.169
<i>Commonly used by</i>
<i>the elite mercenaries</i>

27:51.169 --> 27:53.505
<i>known as gallowglass,</i>
<i>the well-balanced sword</i>

27:53.505 --> 27:55.591
<i>complemented their superior</i>
<i>fighting techniques</i>

27:55.591 --> 27:58.343
<i>that were revered throughout</i>
<i>Ireland in the Middle Ages.</i>

27:58.343 --> 28:01.305
<i>Although warriors such as the</i>
<i>gallowglass no longer exist,</i>

28:01.305 --> 28:03.473
<i>the weapon's symbolism</i>
<i>is still represented</i>

28:03.473 --> 28:05.893
<i>in popular culture today</i>
<i>and can be seen on</i>

28:05.893 --> 28:07.895
<i>the television show</i>
<i>"Game of Thrones,"</i>

28:07.895 --> 28:10.314
<i>where one of the most feared</i>
<i>characters, The Mountain,</i>

28:10.314 --> 28:11.815
<i>wields his ring-hilted sword.</i>

28:11.815 --> 28:14.318
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:14.318 --> 28:16.153
You'll have five days
at your home forges

28:16.153 --> 28:17.946
in which to complete
this challenge.

28:17.946 --> 28:20.407
Your blades must meet
the following parameters.

28:20.407 --> 28:22.242
The length of your blade
must be between

28:22.242 --> 28:24.202
29 and 31 inches in length.

28:24.202 --> 28:26.121
It must be double edged
and include a fuller

28:26.121 --> 28:27.915
on both sides of the blade

28:27.915 --> 28:31.001
that runs at least 3/4
the length of the blade.

28:31.001 --> 28:33.045
It must have
an S-shaped guard

28:33.045 --> 28:35.839
with forked terminals that have
at least three prongs

28:35.839 --> 28:37.716
on each terminal.

28:37.716 --> 28:40.677
Additionally, you must include
a ringed pommel

28:40.677 --> 28:42.846
through which
you can see the tang.

28:42.846 --> 28:44.765
<i>- Making the sword has me</i>

28:44.765 --> 28:47.225
<i>both terrified and excited</i>
<i>at the same time.</i>

28:47.225 --> 28:48.435
I think five days
will get me more time

28:48.435 --> 28:50.354
to focus on the details,

28:50.354 --> 28:52.481
<i>but it's a bigger challenge</i>
<i>as well with a lot more</i>

28:52.481 --> 28:55.150
<i>at stake now that</i>
<i>there are only two of us.</i>

28:55.150 --> 28:57.527
- Bladesmiths,
after five days

28:57.527 --> 28:58.904
you will return
and present your swords

28:58.904 --> 29:00.280
to our panel
of expert judges.

29:00.280 --> 29:02.157
And after they've
thoroughly tested them

29:02.157 --> 29:05.118
and inspected the quality
of your work,

29:05.118 --> 29:07.329
they'll declare one of you the
"Forged in Fire" champion

29:07.329 --> 29:10.540
who walks out of here with
a check for $10,000.

29:10.540 --> 29:12.417
Good luck, bladesmiths.
We'll see you in five days.

29:12.417 --> 29:13.752
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:13.752 --> 29:14.711
- Good luck.
- Good luck, man.

29:14.711 --> 29:18.507
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:18.507 --> 29:20.676
<i>- It's day one, and I'm ready</i>
<i>to get started.</i>

29:20.676 --> 29:21.969
It feels pretty good
to be back home

29:21.969 --> 29:23.804
with the tools
I'm familiar with.

29:23.804 --> 29:25.973
<i>I've never made a sword</i>
<i>even similar to this.</i>

29:25.973 --> 29:28.976
<i>This will be the largest blade</i>
<i>that I've forged.</i>

29:28.976 --> 29:30.894
So I'm going to have to do
some figuring out on that.

29:30.894 --> 29:32.688
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:32.688 --> 29:35.357
Okay, gotta thin this out
and draw it out now.

29:35.357 --> 29:41.905
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:41.905 --> 29:43.824
<i>I'm going in for my first heat</i>
<i>on the steel.</i>

29:43.824 --> 29:45.242
<i>I go to the power hammer.</i>

29:45.242 --> 29:46.618
Within about
four or five strikes,

29:46.618 --> 29:48.787
<i>it stops on me.</i>

29:48.787 --> 29:51.498
<i>I've had no problems</i>
<i>with it before.</i>

29:51.498 --> 29:56.086
It chooses now for the
little gremlins to show up.

29:56.086 --> 29:59.131
Now I've got to start fixing
equipment instead of forging,

29:59.131 --> 30:01.883
<i>which is not what</i>
<i>I had planned for today.</i>

30:01.883 --> 30:03.301
Looks like two
of my retaining screws

30:03.301 --> 30:04.886
have backed out.

30:04.886 --> 30:06.972
If I don't get
the power hammer fixed,

30:06.972 --> 30:10.267
<i>the entire schedule that</i>
<i>I've had in my head for this</i>

30:10.267 --> 30:11.601
<i>is out the window.</i>

30:11.601 --> 30:14.604
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:14.604 --> 30:16.648
Back in business.

30:16.648 --> 30:18.900
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:18.900 --> 30:20.944
<i>It's not perfect.</i>

30:20.944 --> 30:22.237
<i>There's a few things I still</i>
<i>need to tweak on it,</i>

30:22.237 --> 30:23.947
but I need to start
moving steel.

30:23.947 --> 30:26.783
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:26.783 --> 30:29.411
<i>- I'm back at my home forge</i>
<i>in Fletcher, North Carolina.</i>

30:29.411 --> 30:31.413
It's the start of day one.

30:31.413 --> 30:34.332
<i>My shop's pretty well suited</i>
<i>for making the sword,</i>

30:34.332 --> 30:35.917
<i>but I do want to make</i>
<i>a fullering jig</i>

30:35.917 --> 30:37.502
instead of
hand-hammering it in.

30:37.502 --> 30:40.672
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:40.672 --> 30:42.674
<i>I've never done</i>
<i>a fullering jig before.</i>

30:42.674 --> 30:44.092
I usually ground in;

30:44.092 --> 30:45.427
I don't want to grind
this one in.

30:45.427 --> 30:46.595
I actually want to do it
with a tool.

30:46.595 --> 30:52.434
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:52.434 --> 30:54.394
Right now, I'm gonna
try my die out that's

30:54.394 --> 30:56.313
made on some mild steel,

30:56.313 --> 30:58.982
and then I'm gonna start
just working on my sword.

30:58.982 --> 31:03.612
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:03.612 --> 31:06.698
<i>I've spent an hour working on</i>
<i>this jig, and it breaks.</i>

31:06.698 --> 31:08.700
Just have to scrap it
and do it all by hand.

31:08.700 --> 31:11.328
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:11.328 --> 31:12.704
Steel's moving really good.

31:12.704 --> 31:14.331
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:14.331 --> 31:15.791
<i>I got a lot of work</i>
<i>to do, but</i>

31:15.791 --> 31:18.710
so far, I feel really good.

31:18.710 --> 31:20.462
<i>- I'm satisfied with</i>
<i>my progress.</i>

31:20.462 --> 31:22.506
I'd like to be
a little bit farther along.

31:22.506 --> 31:24.382
<i>Having the breakdown</i>
<i>on some of my tools</i>

31:24.382 --> 31:26.343
<i>slowed me down a little bit</i>
<i>more than I was hoping.</i>

31:26.343 --> 31:28.428
<i>By the end of the day,</i>
<i>I'd like to go to heat treat</i>

31:28.428 --> 31:30.972
and temper tonight.

31:30.972 --> 31:32.474
<i>Today, the hard part is going</i>

31:32.474 --> 31:34.434
to be getting the fullers
lined up and even.

31:34.434 --> 31:36.228
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:36.228 --> 31:37.813
<i>I've never made fullers</i>
<i>this length before.</i>

31:37.813 --> 31:39.648
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:39.648 --> 31:41.399
<i>The difficulty</i>
<i>with a fuller this size</i>

31:41.399 --> 31:43.193
<i>is keeping everything straight</i>
<i>and in line</i>

31:43.193 --> 31:46.154
<i>for a much longer travel path</i>
<i>on the fuller.</i>

31:46.154 --> 31:48.949
If I grind through all the way,
then it's trash.

31:48.949 --> 31:50.909
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:50.909 --> 31:52.452
<i>I need the quench to go right</i>

31:52.452 --> 31:54.287
<i>'cause if I have</i>
<i>to start over now,</i>

31:54.287 --> 31:56.248
<i>it's going to put me</i>
<i>way behind.</i>

31:56.248 --> 31:57.999
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:57.999 --> 32:00.001
<i>To catch back up to this point</i>

32:00.001 --> 32:01.711
<i>and still be able to get</i>
<i>the handle all the way I want,</i>

32:01.711 --> 32:03.255
<i>I'd be pushing it to finish.</i>

32:03.255 --> 32:05.882
So I really need things
to go right.

32:05.882 --> 32:09.136
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:09.136 --> 32:10.554
Got a little bit of
a wiggle in it.

32:10.554 --> 32:11.847
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:11.847 --> 32:13.515
<i>The steel's hard.</i>

32:13.515 --> 32:14.641
<i>I've got a little bit of</i>
<i>a warp in it,</i>

32:14.641 --> 32:16.268
<i>but I've got enough steel left</i>

32:16.268 --> 32:18.061
<i>that I've still got</i>
<i>to grind away</i>

32:18.061 --> 32:19.354
<i>that I don't think</i>
<i>that's going to be an issue.</i>

32:19.354 --> 32:20.772
Should be as easy
as eating pancakes.

32:20.772 --> 32:22.607
All right.

32:22.607 --> 32:25.652
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:25.652 --> 32:28.822
- I just started day three,
and I'm ready to go.

32:28.822 --> 32:30.949
<i>I have an issue with my sword.</i>

32:30.949 --> 32:33.160
<i>It's a little thin up</i>
<i>by the tang.</i>

32:33.160 --> 32:36.246
I'm going to put a few beads
of weld on it to strengthen it.

32:36.246 --> 32:37.873
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:37.873 --> 32:38.999
<i>Since I haven't heat-treated</i>
<i>it yet,</i>

32:38.999 --> 32:40.458
<i>it shouldn't hurt anything.</i>

32:40.458 --> 32:42.252
Probably the only problem
I can see is that

32:42.252 --> 32:44.212
<i>it could be brittle.</i>

32:44.212 --> 32:46.715
<i>I mean, when they do</i>
<i>the strength tests on it,</i>

32:46.715 --> 32:48.592
there's a possibility that
the welds could break off.

32:48.592 --> 32:50.552
But I hope not.

32:50.552 --> 32:52.554
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:52.554 --> 32:54.097
[bleep]

32:54.097 --> 32:55.891
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:55.891 --> 32:57.601
Just made my blade worse than
I--I started.

32:57.601 --> 32:59.019
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:59.019 --> 33:01.104
<i>I kind of melted the edge.</i>

33:01.104 --> 33:03.356
<i>I burned into the steel</i>
<i>deeper than I wanted to go.</i>

33:03.356 --> 33:04.983
<i>It caused a pretty big hole.</i>

33:04.983 --> 33:06.109
Now I've really destroyed it.

33:09.487 --> 33:10.488
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:10.488 --> 33:12.699
[bleep]

33:12.699 --> 33:15.702
Just made my blade worse
than I--I started.

33:15.702 --> 33:18.079
Mind's flu--flustered
right now.

33:18.079 --> 33:19.664
It kind of melted the edge.

33:19.664 --> 33:21.374
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:21.374 --> 33:23.376
<i>Now I'm kind of</i>
<i>second-guessing myself.</i>

33:23.376 --> 33:25.670
Should I be welding this
or should I just start over?

33:25.670 --> 33:27.881
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:27.881 --> 33:29.633
<i>I'm going to do a stack weld</i>
<i>and build it up that way.</i>

33:29.633 --> 33:31.885
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:31.885 --> 33:33.803
<i>My welding finally worked.</i>

33:33.803 --> 33:36.640
The thickness is
more than I had before,

33:36.640 --> 33:38.934
so I'm gonna stop welding now
and start grinding.

33:38.934 --> 33:41.519
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:41.519 --> 33:44.314
<i>- Day four, gotten most of</i>
<i>the hardware built.</i>

33:44.314 --> 33:46.608
<i>Now I have to work on</i>
<i>the assembly.</i>

33:46.608 --> 33:47.817
Kind of in
the home stretch now.

33:47.817 --> 33:49.361
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:49.361 --> 33:50.362
<i>I'm going to use</i>
<i>some liquid steel</i>

33:50.362 --> 33:53.031
<i>to assemble the guard.</i>

33:53.031 --> 33:55.867
<i>Fit up the handle</i>
<i>with two-part epoxy.</i>

33:55.867 --> 33:58.119
<i>I do have a pin hole</i>
<i>in the tang</i>

33:58.119 --> 33:59.663
<i>just so that I have</i>
<i>a mechanical hole</i>

33:59.663 --> 34:01.581
<i>as well as</i>
<i>an adhesive hole,</i>

34:01.581 --> 34:02.999
<i>and then it's just a matter</i>
<i>of getting everything</i>

34:02.999 --> 34:04.376
<i>fitted up before it hardens.</i>

34:04.376 --> 34:05.627
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:05.627 --> 34:07.379
<i>I've got the sword together.</i>

34:07.379 --> 34:08.880
It looks like
a battle-worthy weapon.

34:08.880 --> 34:11.466
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:11.466 --> 34:13.134
<i>- It's the start of day five.</i>

34:13.134 --> 34:15.887
I have to completely assemble
my sword today

34:15.887 --> 34:17.806
and do all my detail work
to it.

34:17.806 --> 34:19.599
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:19.599 --> 34:22.769
<i>I had a pretty good bow</i>
<i>in the blade</i>

34:22.769 --> 34:25.689
last night before temper,
and I got most of it out.

34:25.689 --> 34:28.233
There's still some in it.

34:28.233 --> 34:31.236
I'm such a perfectionist.
It's really bothering me.

34:31.236 --> 34:32.529
Snap.

34:32.529 --> 34:35.240
[laughs, snorts]

34:35.240 --> 34:37.033
<i>Right now,</i>

34:37.033 --> 34:39.703
<i>I'm engraving</i>
<i>Celtic runes on here.</i>

34:39.703 --> 34:42.414
This one means family
or relationships.

34:42.414 --> 34:44.916
'Cause I made a bunch of new
"Forged in Fire" family.

34:44.916 --> 34:47.836
This one means happiness
or success.

34:47.836 --> 34:48.920
All done.

34:48.920 --> 34:51.715
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:51.715 --> 34:53.300
<i>I look forward to going back</i>

34:53.300 --> 34:54.926
<i>and seeing how</i>
<i>my blade tests out.</i>

34:54.926 --> 34:57.846
<i>And just--I'm glad</i>
<i>it's over right now.</i>

34:57.846 --> 34:59.514
I can finally
get some sleep, maybe.

34:59.514 --> 35:04.102
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:04.102 --> 35:07.355
- Jason, Shawn,
welcome back to The Forge.

35:07.355 --> 35:09.357
You fellas have had five days
at your home forges

35:09.357 --> 35:11.943
to work on your
Irish ring swords.

35:11.943 --> 35:13.612
Jason, how did it go?

35:13.612 --> 35:15.655
- It was rougher than
I'd thought it'd be.

35:15.655 --> 35:18.158
<i>The blade is made out of 5160</i>

35:18.158 --> 35:20.785
<i>and my pommel ring</i>
<i>is made out of a hammer.</i>

35:20.785 --> 35:23.204
<i>So the whole thing's</i>
<i>high carbon steel.</i>

35:23.204 --> 35:24.539
I'm happy with it.
- Great.

35:24.539 --> 35:26.625
Shawn, how did it go for you?

35:26.625 --> 35:28.627
- It was a little outside my
comfort zone, but it was fun.

35:28.627 --> 35:29.836
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:29.836 --> 35:31.212
<i>The blade is 5160.</i>

35:31.212 --> 35:32.922
<i>The guard and the ring hilt</i>

35:32.922 --> 35:35.342
<i>are actually railroad spike</i>
<i>mild steel.</i>

35:35.342 --> 35:39.220
<i>The handle is a cherry wood</i>
<i>core with a leather risers.</i>

35:39.220 --> 35:41.222
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:41.222 --> 35:43.683
- Well, gentlemen, now it's
time for our weapons test.

35:43.683 --> 35:46.603
Doug?

35:46.603 --> 35:50.565
- All right, bladesmiths,
this is the KEAL test.

35:50.565 --> 35:52.192
To find out what kind of
lethal damage

35:52.192 --> 35:54.736
your Irish ring-hilted
swords can do,

35:54.736 --> 35:56.946
I will take your weapon
and deliver killing blows

35:56.946 --> 35:59.115
on this feral boar carcass.

35:59.115 --> 36:00.867
Jason, you're up first.
You ready?

36:00.867 --> 36:02.786
- I am.
- Let's do this.

36:02.786 --> 36:04.704
- I'm very nervous right now.

36:04.704 --> 36:08.458
My biggest concern is, my blade
is warped at the tip.

36:08.458 --> 36:10.460
Uh, that may affect the usage.

36:10.460 --> 36:14.214
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:14.214 --> 36:17.133
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

36:17.133 --> 36:24.015
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:29.729 --> 36:31.981
- All right, Jason,
first up.

36:31.981 --> 36:34.401
When I grab onto it,
it feels good in the hands.

36:34.401 --> 36:36.111
A good fit.

36:36.111 --> 36:39.072
Now, swinging this is sweet.

36:39.072 --> 36:43.410
You have a very sharp edge
that cuts easily

36:43.410 --> 36:44.994
into this wild board carcass.

36:44.994 --> 36:45.954
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:45.954 --> 36:47.497
It will KEAL.

36:47.497 --> 36:49.332
Good job, Jason.
- Thank you.

36:49.332 --> 36:51.126
- All right, Shawn,
you ready?

36:51.126 --> 36:53.837
- Yes, sir.
- Let's do this.

36:53.837 --> 36:55.547
<i>- Having hunted boar,</i>

36:55.547 --> 36:56.923
<i>I know that the hides</i>
<i>are really thick.</i>

36:56.923 --> 36:58.466
It's not going to be
an easy test.

36:58.466 --> 37:00.593
<i>I'm confident but nervous.</i>

37:00.593 --> 37:02.303
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:02.303 --> 37:05.265
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

37:05.265 --> 37:12.230
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:13.314 --> 37:14.607
- Ooh.

37:14.607 --> 37:17.569
<i>[heavy metal music continues]</i>

37:17.569 --> 37:19.738
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:24.200 --> 37:26.119
- All right, Shawn, let's talk
about your weapon right here.

37:26.119 --> 37:28.413
First up, when I grabbed
onto the handle,

37:28.413 --> 37:30.248
it's got a good feel
to that.

37:30.248 --> 37:32.041
I like that you put
some grooves in there,

37:32.041 --> 37:34.043
'cause it fits nicely to where
my hand locks into it,

37:34.043 --> 37:36.421
and I get a very secure fit.

37:36.421 --> 37:37.630
A little heavier,

37:37.630 --> 37:40.842
but the weight helps
push and cut

37:40.842 --> 37:42.969
into this wild board carcass.

37:42.969 --> 37:46.222
And most of all,
it will KEAL.

37:46.222 --> 37:47.932
- Thank you, sir.
- Good job.

37:47.932 --> 37:51.227
Ben?

37:51.227 --> 37:53.688
- Welcome to the strength test.
The dreaded ice chop.

37:53.688 --> 37:55.440
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:55.440 --> 37:57.358
To test the strength
and durability of your swords

37:57.358 --> 37:59.068
as well as their
overall construction,

37:59.068 --> 38:01.488
I'm going to be chopping
mercilessly

38:01.488 --> 38:03.281
into this unforgiving
block of ice.

38:03.281 --> 38:05.533
Remember, this test is all
about what that ice does

38:05.533 --> 38:06.910
to your ring-hilted swords

38:06.910 --> 38:08.411
and not what your swords
do to the ice.

38:08.411 --> 38:09.746
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:09.746 --> 38:10.914
Jason, you're up first.
You ready?

38:10.914 --> 38:12.832
- Yeah. Go ahead.
- Good.

38:12.832 --> 38:14.501
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:14.501 --> 38:17.420
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

38:17.420 --> 38:19.964
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:19.964 --> 38:21.090
[ice chunk thunks]

38:21.090 --> 38:26.888
♪ ♪

38:26.888 --> 38:28.765
[ice chunk thunks]

38:30.892 --> 38:33.269
Well, Jason,
first thing's first.

38:33.269 --> 38:35.855
<i>The warp--I think that</i>
<i>it being off-center</i>

38:35.855 --> 38:37.732
made it rotate
in my hand.

38:37.732 --> 38:40.985
But the balance on the sword,
as you can see, is beautiful.

38:40.985 --> 38:43.822
It's comfortable to wield,
and it sure held up.

38:43.822 --> 38:45.281
Well done.
- Thank you.

38:45.281 --> 38:47.075
- Shawn, you're up.
How you feeling?

38:47.075 --> 38:48.409
- Nervous but excited.

38:48.409 --> 38:52.163
- All right.
Let's do it.

38:52.163 --> 38:55.458
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:55.458 --> 38:58.628
<i>[heavy metal music]</i>

38:58.628 --> 39:01.339
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:01.339 --> 39:02.298
[ice chunk thunks]

39:02.298 --> 39:06.177
♪ ♪

39:08.221 --> 39:11.641
- Nice.

39:11.641 --> 39:15.103
- Well, Shawn, the weight on
this is a little tip heavy.

39:15.103 --> 39:18.022
I would've liked a little bit
more counterbalance on it.

39:18.022 --> 39:20.817
But that being said, it's still
a lot of fun to swing.

39:20.817 --> 39:22.110
Your edge held up beautifully.

39:22.110 --> 39:24.988
Everything's right and tight.

39:24.988 --> 39:26.531
Well done.
- Thank you, sir.

39:26.531 --> 39:27.824
- Next up is
the sharpness test,

39:27.824 --> 39:29.242
and for that,
I give you to Dave.

39:29.242 --> 39:31.202
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:31.202 --> 39:32.704
- Okay, gentlemen,

39:32.704 --> 39:34.038
now, to test the sharpness
of your blade,

39:34.038 --> 39:35.665
I'll be cutting through
this sugarcane.

39:35.665 --> 39:37.500
I'll use both edges
of your blade.

39:37.500 --> 39:39.085
Now, unlike
the strength test,

39:39.085 --> 39:41.504
this is all about what
your blades do to that target.

39:41.504 --> 39:43.006
I want to see those cuts
nice and clean.

39:43.006 --> 39:44.799
Not canes broken
or pushed out of the way.

39:44.799 --> 39:45.925
Jason, you're up first.
Are you ready?

39:45.925 --> 39:47.302
- I am.
- Okay.

39:47.302 --> 39:52.849
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:52.849 --> 39:55.810
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

39:55.810 --> 40:02.775
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:04.861 --> 40:07.155
All right, Jason,
your handle construction--

40:07.155 --> 40:09.657
you can see how square
that is right there.

40:09.657 --> 40:13.453
When I was in my backhand cut,
I actually got into those canes

40:13.453 --> 40:15.079
and then it rolled.

40:15.079 --> 40:17.206
Your tang is now kind of
kicking off to one side.

40:17.206 --> 40:19.208
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:19.208 --> 40:21.461
So that probably happened

40:21.461 --> 40:23.713
as that blade caught
that last cane

40:23.713 --> 40:25.173
and yanked down.

40:25.173 --> 40:27.300
But, uh, it's definitely
a sharp blade.

40:27.300 --> 40:28.760
Really nice.

40:28.760 --> 40:30.219
Shawn, you're up.
Are you ready?

40:30.219 --> 40:31.888
- Yes, sir.
- Okay.

40:31.888 --> 40:34.974
<i>- After two tests,</i>
<i>it's--it's really close.</i>

40:34.974 --> 40:37.727
He did get a little bit
of a warp in his blade.

40:37.727 --> 40:40.939
<i>My sword is a little heavier</i>
<i>towards the tip.</i>

40:40.939 --> 40:44.275
It could either benefit or
be a drawback at this point.

40:44.275 --> 40:45.985
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:49.781 --> 40:55.912
♪ ♪

40:55.912 --> 40:57.455
- Nice.

40:57.455 --> 40:58.873
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:58.873 --> 41:00.458
- Okay.

41:00.458 --> 41:01.918
First up,
your handle construction.

41:01.918 --> 41:03.044
I like a lot.

41:03.044 --> 41:04.754
It's not rotating in my hand.

41:04.754 --> 41:06.339
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:06.339 --> 41:09.258
It's a heavier sword,
but the cuts are clean.

41:09.258 --> 41:11.052
It's definitely a sharp blade.
I like that.

41:11.052 --> 41:12.553
Well done.
- Thank you.

41:12.553 --> 41:15.640
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:15.640 --> 41:17.141
- Jason, Shawn,

41:17.141 --> 41:18.851
The judges' deliberation
is complete.

41:18.851 --> 41:20.395
They have made their
final decision.

41:20.395 --> 41:22.438
The next "Forged in Fire"
champion is...

41:22.438 --> 41:26.275
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:26.275 --> 41:28.403
Shawn.

41:28.403 --> 41:30.738
Congratulations, you're the new
"Forged in Fire" champion.

41:30.738 --> 41:33.908
Jason, unfortunately your blade
didn't make the cut.

41:33.908 --> 41:35.702
Doug Marcaida will explain.

41:35.702 --> 41:38.705
- Jason, your sword had
great balance and was sharp,

41:38.705 --> 41:41.833
but your sword also took a bend
on the sharpness test.

41:41.833 --> 41:43.334
And for that reason,
we're sending you home.

41:43.334 --> 41:45.294
- Okay.
- Jason,

41:45.294 --> 41:47.672
please surrender your blade.

41:47.672 --> 41:50.091
- I would've like to have won.
[chuckles]

41:50.091 --> 41:51.843
<i>But, uh, I'm proud of</i>
<i>what I've done,</i>

41:51.843 --> 41:54.929
<i>I mean, throughout this</i>
<i>whole series of tests.</i>

41:54.929 --> 41:58.683
I made a strong, sharp blade
that performed equally as well.

41:58.683 --> 42:00.685
So I--I'm happy with it.

42:00.685 --> 42:02.854
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:02.854 --> 42:04.480
- Shawn, congratulations.

42:04.480 --> 42:06.274
You're the new
"Forged in Fire" champion,

42:06.274 --> 42:08.943
and that's a title that comes
with a check for $10,000.

42:08.943 --> 42:10.403
How do you feel about that?

42:10.403 --> 42:11.696
- It doesn't suck.

42:11.696 --> 42:13.531
[laughter]
- No, it does not.

42:13.531 --> 42:17.160
Shawn, please present
your blade to the judges.

42:17.160 --> 42:19.704
<i>- This whole experience,</i>
<i>it's pushed me physically.</i>

42:19.704 --> 42:21.205
<i>It's pushed me mentally.</i>

42:21.205 --> 42:22.832
Parts of it have been
pretty brutal.

42:22.832 --> 42:24.917
Thank you, guys.

42:24.917 --> 42:26.169
<i>And I wouldn't trade a minute</i>
<i>of it for anything.</i>

42:26.169 --> 42:27.670
I've--I've had the time
of my life.

42:27.670 --> 42:33.634
<i>♪ ♪</i>
